qas.question: What has a three-way distinction in regards to stops and affricates?

context: <a0_0>Wu Chinese<a0_0/> has a three-way distinction in <b4_0>stops and affricates<b4_0/>: <a1_0>/p pʰ b/<a1_0/>. In addition to aspirated and unaspirated consonants, there is a series of <b5_0><b8_0>muddy consonants<b8_0/><b5_0/>, like <b7_0>/b/<b7_0/>. These are pronounced with <a3_0>slack or breathy<a3_0/> voice: that is, they are weakly voiced. <a2_0><b6_0>Muddy consonants<b6_0/><a2_0/> as initial cause a syllable to be pronounced with low pitch or light (陽 yáng) tone.
